Tutorial - Introduction to ggplot2

Highlighting Disproportionate Impact

Published

October 28, 2022

Halloween Town University (HTU) wants to visualize the transfer rates of their students by ethnicity and highlight any disproportionate impact among the population. They want the visual to conform to their hideous internal branding guidelines, while communicating the critical pieces of information.

Intro

This tutorial is designed to introduce the ggplot2 R package to IR professionals in the R working group, by visualizing disproportionate impact found within transfer rate across ethnicity. NOTE: The data used is artificially generated and provided by the DisImpact package.

Specifically, we apply PPG methodology to the student_equity data.frame from the DisImpact package using the di_ppg function. Then, we visualize the results using functions from ggplot2. This is a common and important task for most research departments.

Our Goal

This is what we are working towards:

This is the code to generate that graph:

# Load our Libraries ####
library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

# Clean our data ####
di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)
di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]
di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

# Declare some constants ####
# Halloween Colors: Google "Halloween Colors Hex Codes"
clr_purple <- "#902EBB"
clr_orange <- "#F4831B"
clr_green  <- "#63C328"
clr_red    <- "#D02823"
clr_dark   <- "#250d03"

# Create Graph ####
ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', aes(fill = di_indicator)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = unique(di_data$reference), color = clr_green, size = 2) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), color = clr_purple, nudge_y = .02) +
    geom_text(aes(y = unique(reference), x = "Black", label = paste0("Overall: ", round(unique(reference), 2)*100, "%")), color = clr_green, nudge_y = -.02) +
    labs(
        title = "Inequities are scary...", # Add title
        subtitle = "Visualizing Disproportionate Impact with ggplot2", # Add subtitle
        x = NULL, # This removes the x-axis label
        y = "Transfer Rate", # This modifies the y-axis label,
        caption = "Data Source: DisImpact R Package",
        fill = NULL # This removes the legend title, but we could easily rename it.
    ) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("DI" = clr_orange, "No DI" = clr_dark)) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent,
                       expand = expansion(mult = c(0, .02))) +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = clr_red),
        legend.position = c(.5, .9),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank()
    )

Throughout this tutorial, Iâll do my best to explain each line of the above code and how you might change it to fit your needs.

Set Up

Iâd recommend running all of the code in this tutorial, so you can see the output from each step, as we walk through it. To follow along with this tutorial, youâll need to have two packages installed:

  • ggplot2

  • DisImpact

You can install both packages with the following code in an R session:

install.packages(c('ggplot2', 'DisImpact'))

If you are following along in your own R session, once the packages are installed, you should load each package so we can use the functions contained. To do this, add the following code to the top of your script:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

Quick Disproportionate Impact Analysis

Our goal in this section is to quickly get some data that we can start to visualize. In the real world, this part is the most important and may likely take the most time. However, since our focus is on visualization, we haphazardly âanalyzeâ some artificial data and take the results at face-value.

The DisImpact packages comes with some toy data that saves us from having to read any data into R. The data is called student_equity and it looks like this (selecting only a few columns):

Weâre going to use the di_ppg function from the DisImpact package to calculate the Disproportionate Impact across ethnicities for studentsâ Transfer Rates. The di_ppg function is our way of using the PPG Disproportionate Impact Methodology as explained here: CCCCO PPG Intro

We will name our results di_data:

# Load Necessary Packages
library(ggplot2)   # Package to visualize data
library(DisImpact) # Package with functions for calculating DI

# Step 1: Analyze Transfer Rates by Ethnicity using PPG and assign results to an object named "di_data"
di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data is a data.frame (like student_equity). I think of data.frames like excel sheets. They are tabular, with column names and rows.

The only other thing I want to change about this data is our âdi_indicatorâ variable. Instead of having a â1â for disproportionately impacted and a â0â for not disproportionately impacted, I want to use the labels âDIâ and âNo DIâ, respectively. This will make our visual easier to interpret later on:

# Load Necessary Packages
library(ggplot2)   # Package to visualize data
library(DisImpact) # Package with functions for calculating DI

# Step 1: Analyze Transfer Rates by Ethnicity using PPG and assign results to an object named "di_data"
di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

# Step 2: Select only the columns we'll use
di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

# Step 3: Recode the DI Indicator Column
di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

Building layers

Plots created by ggplot2 are composed of âlayersâ. We start with a blank canvas, then use the data to create an x and y axis layer. Then we add a layer of rectangles for our bar chart, then we add a layer of text to label our bars. ggplot2 handles a lot of the positioning work for us, but provides tools to let us customize where/how each element of each layer appears.

Geoms and Aesthetics

Two fundamental ggplot2 ideas are âgeomsâ and âaestheticsâ. geoms (geometry objects) are shapes on the graph, like squares, circles, lines, and (less intuitively) text. Aesthetics are attributes of those shapes: fill, linetype, size, opacity, color, etcâ¦

We can have multiple geoms in a single graph - think of a line graph with a point at each connection and text displaying each value. We can map our data to various aesthetics (abbreviated aes in ggplot2) of the shapes - think changing the color of a bar in a bar graph depending on whether our data shows DI or not.

With data, geoms, and aesthetics, we can create a basic graph.

Part 1: Bare Minimum - Get A Basic Bar Chart

Our first step is to create a canvas. We do that with the ggplot function, providing it with our DI data and instructions for which columns to map to the x-axis and y-axis.

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct))

Our x and y axes are visible. But now we want to add some shapes. In order to add another layer, we actually use the plus sign (+) before our next call.

Letâs add rectangles to create a bar chart, by adding (+) a geom:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity')

The stat='identity' argument is us telling ggplot2 that weâve already summarized the numbers. The default value is stat='count' which would count our y-axis variable, if we didnât specify that weâve already summarized it.

Now we have a bar graph.

Add Text

We want to label each bar with the y-axis value using text. To do that, we can add a geom_text and specify that we want to use the outcome variable as our label:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
    geom_text(aes(label = pct))

Clean Up Text

That many decimal places looks ugly, so letâs clean up that data on the fly. We can do this by rounding the percentage to two places, mutliply it by 100, and paste a percentage sign on the end:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")))

I want the text to be slightly above the bar, instead of overlapping. Currently, ggplot2 is using the y-axis value to position our text. We want to nudge it slightly above. There is an argument specifically for this purpose:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), nudge_y = .02)

Note

If you look at the help documentation for geom_bar and geom_text, youâll see that they require a mapping and a data argument. We donât specifically provide those arguments, so how does ggplot2 know that we want to use our di_data and that the x-axis should be Ethnicity and the y-axis should be outcome (in our case Transfer rate). Well, subsequent layers will inherit those arguments from our original call to ggplot. This is useful because it prevents us from having to specify the same data and mappings for each layer. However, if needed, we can still override those defaults by specifying new data or mapping arguments. In our case, though, using the defaults is what we want.

Highlighting DI

Next we want to call attention to those populations who have experienced Disproportionate Impact. In our di_data data.frame, there is a column called âdi_indicatorâ, that shows a âDIâ for those with DI and a âNo DIâ for those without.

We want the aesthetic of our geom_bars to change, based on âdi_indicatorâ. So within our geom_bar call, lets add a call to aes(). We use the fill aesthetic, to fill the shape up with color. The color aesthetic only deals with the color of the lines.

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', aes(fill = di_indicator)) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), nudge_y = .02)

A legend appeared helps us distinguish what each color means. Cool!

Adding Labels

We want to add/modify the graphs labels, so that our audience knows that theyâre looking at. There are many ways to do this, but Iâve only ever used the labs (short for âlabelsâ) function in ggplot2. Iâm not sure if these elements are considered geoms, aesthetics, or something else, but theyâre easy to use. Youâre just gonna have to memorize the arguments or use ?labs to learn more:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', aes(fill = di_indicator)) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), nudge_y = .02) +
    labs(
        title = "Inequities are scary...", # Add title
        subtitle = "Visualizing Disproportionate Impact with ggplot2", # Add subtitle
        x = NULL, # This removes the x-axis label
        y = "Transfer Rate", # This modifies the y-axis label,
        caption = "Data Source: DisImpact R Package",
        fill = NULL # This removes the legend title, but we could easily rename it.
    )

Reference Line

We want to create a horizontal line (geom) that shows us where the Overall Transfer Rate is. We also want to label this line with text to let our audience know what it meant.

Knowing where the âOverall Tranfer Rateâ lives in our data is half of the battle. Itâs located in our di_data data.frame in a variable called reference. In the R console we can see it with the following line of code:

di_data$reference
[1] 0.5264 0.5264 0.5264 0.5264 0.5264 0.5264

Notice how it shows up multiple times? Thatâs because itâs included in each row of the data.frame. If we only want one to show up, we can make a call to the unique function:

unique(di_data$reference)
[1] 0.5264

We can combine this with a geom_hline to our chart like so:

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]

di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', aes(fill = di_indicator)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = unique(di_data$reference)) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), nudge_y = .02) +
    labs(
        title = "Inequities are scary...", # Add title
        subtitle = "Visualizing Disproportionate Impact with ggplot2", # Add subtitle
        x = NULL, # This removes the x-axis label
        y = "Transfer Rate", # This modifies the y-axis label,
        caption = "Data Source: DisImpact R Package",
        fill = NULL # This removes the legend title, but we could easily rename it.
    )

Awesome! Letâs label that line now, so people know what it means. We want to add text (geom) to the line. And it looks like there is space to position the text above the bar for the âBlackâ category. Iâm also creating a more appropriately formatted label at the same time and nudging it a little below the actual reference line:

Custom Colors

The default colors are pretty ugly and donât really help us âhighlightâ the in-need populations. To do that, we want a more muted color for the âNo DIâ students and a louder color for the âDIâ students.

After googling âHalloween Color Hex Codesâ, I found the following âhex codesâ (google it) and am going to add them to our script above our graph code.

Note

Iâm also going to add comments that break our code up into sections, so things are more visually organized.

Weâve just declared our colors. We havenât used them anywhere, so our graph looks unchanged.

In order to specify that âDIâ students should have the color clr_orange and that âNo DIâ students should have the color clr_dark, we need to use scale_fill_manual.

Honestly, I donât know how/why we use a function that starts with scale_, but the fill makes sense, because weâre changing the fill and the manual makes sense cause weâre doing it manually, as opposed to letting gglpot2 handle the color choices.

library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

# Clean our data ####
di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)

    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', aes(fill = di_indicator)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = unique(di_data$reference)) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), nudge_y = .02) +
    geom_text(aes(y = unique(reference), x = "Black", label = paste0("Overall: ", round(unique(reference), 2)*100, "%")), nudge_y = -.02) +
    labs(
        title = "Inequities are scary...", # Add title
        subtitle = "Visualizing Disproportionate Impact with ggplot2", # Add subtitle
        x = NULL, # This removes the x-axis label
        y = "Transfer Rate", # This modifies the y-axis label,
        caption = "Data Source: DisImpact R Package",
        fill = NULL # This removes the legend title, but we could easily rename it.
    ) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("DI" = clr_orange, "No DI" = clr_dark))

Now letâs change the color of our reference line, reference line text, and bar labels. Weâre also going to switch the order of our code to have our geom_hline be âbehindâ the bar labels:

library(DisImpact)

# Prepare our data ####

di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]
di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

clr_orange <- "#F4831B"
clr_green  <- "#63C328"
clr_red    <- "#D02823"
clr_dark   <- "#250d03"

# Create Graph ####

    geom_text(aes(y = unique(reference), x = "Black", label = paste0("Overall: ", round(unique(reference), 2)*100, "%")), color = clr_green, nudge_y = -.02) + # CHANGED HERE

Themes focus on aspect of the visual that are not really concerned with data. We can add our own theme elements with a call to the general theme() function.

Use ?theme to see the never ending list of elements you can manually control. Itâs overwhelming, but useful when you have a very specific look youâre going for. Letâs change the way the Title Text looks:

Now lets change the position of the legend and remove the vertical background lines:

# Load our Libraries ####
library(ggplot2)
library(DisImpact)

# Clean our data ####
di_data <- di_ppg(success = student_equity$Transfer, group = student_equity$Ethnicity)
di_data <- di_data[c("group", "pct", "di_indicator", "reference", "n")]
di_data$di_indicator <- ifelse(di_data$di_indicator == 1, "DI", "No DI")

# Declare some constants ####

clr_orange <- "#F4831B"
clr_green  <- "#63C328"
clr_red    <- "#D02823"
clr_dark   <- "#250d03"

# Create Graph ####
ggplot(data = di_data, mapping = aes(x = group, y = pct)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', aes(fill = di_indicator)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = unique(di_data$reference), color = clr_green, size = 2) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(100 * round(pct, 2), "%")), color = clr_purple, nudge_y = .02) +
    geom_text(aes(y = unique(reference), x = "Black", label = paste0("Overall: ", round(unique(reference), 2)*100, "%")), color = clr_green, nudge_y = -.02) +
    labs(
        title = "Inequities are scary...", # Add title
        subtitle = "Visualizing Disproportionate Impact with ggplot2", # Add subtitle
        x = NULL, # This removes the x-axis label
        y = "Transfer Rate", # This modifies the y-axis label,
        caption = "Data Source: DisImpact R Package",
        fill = NULL # This removes the legend title, but we could easily rename it.
    ) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("DI" = clr_orange, "No DI" = clr_dark)) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = clr_red),
        legend.position = c(.5, .9),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank()
    )

Most arguments within the theme() function, will take calls from the element_* family of functions, like element_text, element_rect, or element_line depending on what kind of element you want to change. Use ggplot2::element_text to read the docs.
